<HEADLINE>
<P>
CORNELIUS COFFEY; TRAINED TUSKEGEE AIRMEN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Cornelius Coffey, 91, a self-taught aviator who trained many of the Tuskegee 
Airmen after a commercial flying school refused to accept him because he was 
black. Coffey and John Robinson, a fellow black mechanic, built a one-seat 
airplane powered by a motorcycle engine and taught themselves to fly.They were 
accepted in a mechanics training program at the Curtiss Wright School of 
Aeronautics in Chicago, but the school wanted to return their tuition when it 
learned they were black. Emil Mack, a white man who ran the auto dealership 
where the two worked as mechanics, threatened to sue and the school relented. 
Two years later, Coffey and Johnson graduated at the top of their class. Coffey 
was the first black man to hold both a pilot's and a mechanic's license. He 
established the Coffey School of Aeronautics and trained more than 1,000 pilots 
from 1938 to 1945, including many of the Tuskegee Airmen, the black pilots who 
flew combat missions in World War II. In Chicago on Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
