<HEADLINE>
<P>
SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA VOICES / A FORUM FOR COMMUNITY ISSUES: SECOND OPINION / 
OTHER MEDIA; LA OPINION; MAKING THE IMMIGRATION DEBATE A RATIONAL ONE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By La Opinion is a Spanish-language daily published in Los Angeles. Translated 
by Kevin Baxter. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 In times of difficulty, immigrants are always blamed for the problems in this 
country. They are accused of taking jobs and of taking advantage of social 
services.They are blamed for delinquency and for the problems in the schools. 
The negative debate about immigration is based on stereotypes. It's simplistic 
and stirs feelings of rejection among the native population, including 
immigrants who are now established here. 
</P>
<P>
 It's a debate that exploits the malaise of the public during difficult times 
and, because of that, it finds fertile soil to give it credibility. It is a 
politically costly debate. 
</P>
<P>
 It is obvious that the debate over immigration has left the rational path and 
that it can become a case of collective hysteria stimulated by politicians and 
opportunists. It is necessary to create the conditions for a rational debate. 
This means putting the phenomenon of immigration in perspective. 
</P>
<P>
 Immigrants are not responsible for the recession or for unemployment. On the 
contrary, they are entrepreneurs, yearning to participate and to be 
incorporated completely in the building of the country that they have chosen as 
their home and the homeland of their children. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Opinion 
</P>
