<HEADLINE>
<P>
PREP BASEBALL 1994 / ORANGE LEAGUE; MAGNOLIA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 1993 RECORDS OVERALL: 9-17 LEAGUE: 7-8 
</P>
<P>
 COACH: RECORD AT SCHOOL John Hangartner: 9-17 04,20,05,06,05 RETURNING 
STARTERS YR. POS. B-T Jason Dangler Sr. OF R-R Matt Nester Sr. OF-P R-R 
04,14,05,06,05 TOP RETURNER YR. POS. B-T Tony Ortiz Sr. 3B R-R 04,17,05,07,05 
TOP NEWCOMERS YR. POS. B-T Matt Draykowski Jr. OF-P R-R Josh Reding Jr. SS-2B 
R-R OUTLOOK 
</P>
<P>
 Hangartner did a good job in his first season, guiding the Sentinels to a 
fourth-place finish after a season in the cellar. The former standout Sentinel 
shortstop said he expects continued improvement. "We have a lot of talented 
guys, and I am looking forward to a very successful year," Hangartner said. "We 
have a strong pitching staff and a very sound defense. Barring injuries, I feel 
there is no reason we shouldn't take the Orange League title." The Sentinels 
have experienced success. They finished a half game behind league champion 
Brea-Olinda in 1990 and a game behind the Wildcats in '91. A title this season, 
however, is unlikely. Many coaches have picked Brea-Olinda and Valencia to 
battle for the top spot because of their returning talent. If Magnolia is to 
achieve its goal, however, it will need strong, consistent play from Dangler 
and Nester. Dangler, a swift fielder, batted .483 in league play and is a 
two-time all-league selection. Nester (.333) is expected to be the Sentinels' 
top pitcher. Ortiz (.308) is a leader in the infield. Reding could make a major 
impact. He moves with ease from shortstop to second base and he can pitch. 
Several positions, however, are unsettled. Hangartner is considering many 
options at first base and catcher. Jobs also are open on the pitching staff. 
</P>
