<HEADLINE>
<P>
PAGES; A READER'S LIST OF GOOD READS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By GLEN JUSTICE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Upon retiring, Jane Dienstfrey's dream was to recline in her Connecticut home 
and read. She got her wish -- and a lot more. 
</P>
<P>
 A former editor at the New Yorker, Dienstfrey now reads more than 40 books 
each month to publish Select Fiction, a newsletter highlighting works 
overlooked by bestseller lists. 
</P>
<P>
 "I thought there should be a list somewhere," she said. "I track the authors 
and when someone you haven't heard of keeps popping up, I get the book. I love 
page turners." 
</P>
<P>
 Dienstfrey reviews about 10 books in each edition. The publication -- which 
covers light and heavy fiction -- offers a one-paragraph summary and excerpts 
from other reviews. 
</P>
<P>
 The newsletter has about 300 subscribers, and Dienstfrey said she is getting 
more than 50 calls a day. 
</P>
<P>
 "I think it's the winter," she said. "Not your winter; I've been to L.A. But 
out here, we have a lot of snow." 
</P>
<P>
 Select Fiction (P.O. Box 1041, Sharon, Conn. 06069) costs $6.50 for five 
editions. GLEN JUSTICE 
</P>
</TEXT>
